│           └── Signup.styles.ts
│
└── assets/                     # Images, fonts, icons
```

## Firebase Rules

- Always access Firestore through helper functions in /firebase/, never call firebase directly from a screen.
- Always check for authenticated user before any Firestore read/write.
- Use real-time listeners (onSnapshot) for game lists. Use one-time gets (getDoc) for single game detail.

## Firestore Data Models

### Game Document (`games/{gameId}`)

```ts
{
  title: string
  type: "scrimmage" | "minigame"
  minigameType: string | null        // e.g. "World Cup", "Wembley", "3hit kill"
  surface: "outdoor" | "indoor" | "futsal"
  fieldName: string
  location: { lat: number, lng: number }
  address: string
  date: string                       // ISO format "YYYY-MM-DD"
  time: string                       // "6:00 PM"
  playersMax: number
  playersJoined: string[]            // array of userIds
  createdBy: string                  // userId
  createdAt: Timestamp
}
```

### User Document (`users/{userId}`)

```ts
{
  displayName: string;
  avatar: string | null;
  location: string;
  gamesCreated: number;
  gamesJoined: number;
}
```

## Naming Conventions

- Components: PascalCase filename, e.g. `GameCard.tsx`
- Component stylesheets: PascalCase + `.styles.ts`, e.g. `GameCard.styles.ts`
- Screen stylesheets: PascalCase + `.styles.ts`, e.g. `Home.styles.ts`
- Hooks: camelCase prefixed with "use", e.g. `useGames.ts`
- Firebase helpers: camelCase, e.g. `createGame.ts`, `getGames.ts`
- Types: PascalCase interfaces, e.g. `Game`, `AppUser`

## AI Behavior Rules

- When generating a new component, always include TypeScript types **and** create a matching `.styles.ts` file in `/styles/components/`.
- When generating a new screen, always create a matching `.styles.ts` file in `/styles/screens/`.
- Never put `StyleSheet.create()` inside a component or screen file — always in the matching styles file.
- When writing Firebase functions, always include error handling with try/catch.
- When asked to build a screen, scaffold the full screen with placeholder UI — don't leave empty functions.
- Never install new packages without mentioning it explicitly with the exact install command.
- Always add a comment block at the top of each new file describing what it does.
- If something requires a .env variable (e.g. API keys), flag it clearly with a TODO comment.
- When suggesting changes, only touch the files relevant to the task. Do not refactor unrelated code.
